      <hedline>
        <hl1>What Would the Founders Say?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Richard A Altman letter on Michael Novak's Sept 4 article defends view that religion should be kept out of public life</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Michael Novak's comparison of secularists to Victorians is troubling (Op-Ed, Sept. 4). Many believe that religion should be as private a matter as sex, and that both are too prevalent in our public life (witness their sanctimonious mixture during the Clinton impeachment). Those of us who object are neither anti-religious nor prudish.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Michael Novak's comparison of secularists to Victorians is troubling (Op-Ed, Sept. 4). Many believe that religion should be as private a matter as sex, and that both are too prevalent in our public life (witness their sanctimonious mixture during the Clinton impeachment). Those of us who object are neither anti-religious nor prudish.</p>
        <p>Mr. Novak's appeal to civility and reason in public life is exactly right, but religion is by definition a matter of faith, not rational argument. For that reason alone it is antithetical to public discourse.</p>
        <p>The views of Senator Joseph I. Lieberman and Mr. Novak undermine both the First Amendment's principles of the separation of church and state and the constitutional provision barring any religious test for public office. Whatever the beliefs of the founding fathers may have been, they wisely wrote both provisions into our Constitution.</p>
        <p>RICHARD A. ALTMAN  New York, Sept. 4, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a lawyer.</p>
      </block>
